# Room 48 CAPA: The Basics

## Task 1 Introduction

CAPA (Common Analysis Platform for Artifacts) is a tool by FireEye Mandiant.
- Identifies capabilities in executables (PE, ELF, .NET, shellcode, sandbox reports).
- Uses rules to detect behaviors: network communication, file manipulation, process injection, persistence.
- Encapsulates reverse engineering knowledge into automated analysis.
- Useful for malware analysis, threat hunting, and incident response.

---

## Task 2 Tool Overview: How CAPA Works

- Run CAPA via PowerShell: capa.exe <binary>.
- Options: -v (verbose), -vv (very verbose).
- Sample output (cryptbot.bin): hashes, OS, format, architecture, path.
- Detected capabilities: Defense Evasion, Discovery, Execution, Impact, Persistence.
- MAEC category: Launcher.
- MBC behaviors: obfuscation, HTTP communication, file system actions, memory allocation, process creation.

---

## Task 3 Dissecting CAPA Results Part 1: General Information, MITRE and MAEC

- General Info: Hashes, OS, format, architecture, path.
- MITRE ATT&CK Mapping: Defense Evasion (T1027, T1027.005, T1497.001), Discovery (T1083), 
- Execution (T1059.001, T1129), Impact (T1496), Persistence (T1053.002, T1053.005).
- MAEC: Category “Launcher” → dropping payloads, persistence, C2 communication, executing functions.
- Downloader value → fetching payloads, updates, configs.

---

## Task 4 Dissecting CAPA Results Part 2: Malware Behavior Catalogue (MBC)

- MBC: Catalogue of malware objectives and behaviors, complements MITRE ATT&CK.
- Objectives: Anti-Behavioral Analysis, Anti-Static Analysis, Collection, C2, Credential Access, 
- Defense Evasion, Discovery, Execution, Exfiltration, Impact, Lateral Movement, Persistence, Privilege Escalation.
- Micro-Objectives: PROCESS, MEMORY, COMMUNICATION, DATA.
- Behaviors: Lab Machine Detection [B0009], 
Executable Code Obfuscation [B0032], Command Interpreter [E1059], File Discovery [E1083], Obfuscated Files [E1027].
- Micro-Behaviors: Allocate Memory [C0007], Create Process [C0017], HTTP Communication [C0002], Check String [C0019], 
Encode Data [C0026], File system actions (create, delete, read, write).

---

## Task 5 Dissecting CAPA Results Part 3: Namespaces

CAPA groups rules by Namespaces.
- Top-Level Namespaces (TLN): Anti-Analysis, Collection, Communication, Compiler, Data-Manipulation, 
- Executable, Host-Interaction, Impact, Linking, Load-Code, Persistence, Runtime, Targeting.
Example: reference anti-VM strings::Anti-Analysis/anti-vm/vm-detection.
- Rules are YAML files; capability names match rule names.
- Exceptions: some rules (e.g., cryptocurrency strings) are under Nursery TLN (staging ground for unpolished rules).

---

## Task 6 Dissecting CAPA Results Part 4: Capability

Capabilities: Specific behaviors identified by CAPA rules.
Examples:
- reference anti-VM strings → Anti-Analysis / anti-vm/vm-detection.
- schedule task via schtasks → Persistence / scheduled-tasks.
- reference Base64 string → Data-Manipulation / encoding/base64.
- Each capability links to a YAML rule file.
- Capabilities show what malware can do (e.g., encode data, evade detection, maintain persistence).

---

## Task 7 More Information, More Fun!

Use -vv (very verbose) for detailed results.
Output can be redirected to JSON: capa.exe -j -vv cryptbot.bin > cryptbot_vv.json.
CAPA Web Explorer: Upload JSON to visualize results.
Shows which strings or features triggered rules.
Example:
- Anti-VM strings rule → regex /VMWare/i.
- Scheduled task rule → regex /schtasks/i and /\/create /i.
- Explorer provides filtering, global search, and easier navigation compared to raw text.

