## Tools Used

- CAPA (capa.exe) → static analysis of binaries.
- PowerShell → execution environment for CAPA on Windows.
- CAPA Rule Sets (YAML) → define capabilities, namespaces, and behaviors.
- MITRE ATT&CK Framework → maps tactics and techniques.
- MAEC (Malware Attribute Enumeration and Characterization) → categorizes malware attributes.
- MBC (Malware Behavior Catalogue) → objectives, behaviors, and micro-behaviors.
- CAPA Web Explorer

## Findings

- CAPA automates reverse engineering knowledge.
- Provides structured output aligned with MITRE ATT&CK, MAEC, and MBC.
- Detects obfuscation, persistence, execution, and communication behaviors.
- Namespaces and capabilities organize rules for clarity.
- Verbose mode + Web Explorer reveal exact rule matches.

## Mitigation / Best Practices

- Use CAPA in isolated environments (sandbox/VM).
- Run with verbose options for deeper insights.
- Cross-reference CAPA results with MITRE ATT&CK for incident response.
- Use MAEC/MBC mappings for malware categorization.
- Integrate CAPA into threat hunting workflows.
- Use CAPA Web Explorer for easier analysis of verbose outputs.

## Conclusion

- CAPA is a powerful static analysis tool for malware capabilities.
- Maps behaviors to MITRE ATT&CK, MAEC, and MBC frameworks.
- Helps analysts quickly understand malicious binaries.
- Verbose mode and Web Explorer enhance rule transparency.
- Essential for incident response and defensive security.
